      Oh banks
   =20
 =20

One way to think about it is that the stock market is supposed to be effici=
ent and the market for bank deposits is not. The point of the stock market =
is that a lot of well-informed hedge fund managers and hard-working analyst=
s and Reddit-reading day traders are all competing with each other to find =
out information about each company and use that information to determine th=
e fair value of its stock. The price of a stock changes each second to refl=
ect the information and views collected by the market, and if the market is=
 working well then that price reflects the collective best guess at the lon=
g-term value of the company. In practice the market sometimes tries too har=
d, and stock prices bounce around=C2=A0more than is justified by changes in=
 fundamental information, but this is the goal.
The point of a checking account is that you put your money there and=C2=A0d=
on=E2=80=99t=C2=A0think about it. You=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0compete with =
a bunch of hedge fund managers to understand your bank=E2=80=99s financial =
statements; you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0stay up late reading Reddit for clu=
es about its=C2=A0business prospects; you maybe aren=E2=80=99t even aware o=
f the interest rate that it pays you. A checking account is not a high-risk=
, high-reward financial instrument that you have spent a long time doing du=
e diligence on. It=E2=80=99s just money in the bank.
Economists say that bank deposits are supposed to be =E2=80=9Cinformation-i=
nsensitive,=E2=80=9D and there is a vast corporate-finance and regulatory a=
pparatus to make that mostly true. Most people=E2=80=99s bank accounts, for=
 instance, are insured (up to $250,000) by the=C2=A0Federal Deposit Insuran=
ce Corp., so that even if their bank=C2=A0is=C2=A0just cobwebs and fraud th=
ey still get their money back, which means that they truly=C2=A0don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0need to do any diligence on their bank.
  [1]
 But also banks have capital and liquidity requirements and prudential regu=
lation and access to Federal Reserve lending facilities, so that even if th=
ings go pretty wrong at a bank it will still have enough money to pay out i=
ts depositors, because =E2=80=9Cthe depositors don=E2=80=99t need to worry =
about their deposits=E2=80=9D is kind of the whole point of bank deposits. =
Lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers, regulators, economists =E2=80=94 thi=
nk about these things,=C2=A0so that depositors never have to.
  [2]

Now, this is not always true.=C2=A0The classic story of a bank run is somet=
hing like =E2=80=9Cdeposits suddenly become information-sensitive, and you =
don't want that.=E2=80=9D One way to tell the story of   Silicon Valley Ban=
k=E2=80=99s collapse is that its balance sheet got pretty rickety, sharehol=
ders saw that and said =E2=80=9Cwell that=E2=80=99s fine, you can have a ba=
nk with a rickety balance sheet as long as it keeps its deposits,=E2=80=9D =
and the stock muddled along for a while. But then=C2=A0depositors=C2=A0noti=
ced that the balance sheet was rickety, they pulled their money, and the ba=
nk collapsed instantly. In fact, depositors might have noticed the problem =
because SVB publicly announced a share sale, which put more focus on its pr=
oblems. It=C2=A0actually found enough buyers for the stock=C2=A0at a decent=
 price,=C2=A0but then had to pull the deal because so many deposits had van=
ished: SVB=E2=80=99s shareholders were=C2=A0less=C2=A0information-sensitive=
, briefly, than its depositors.=C2=A0
But the story of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0the second half of this week? =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0in the US regional bank mini-crisis seems to be that the stocks of some =
regional banks are=C2=A0very=C2=A0volatile, while their deposits are not. T=
he shareholders are reading the news and alternately panicking and rejoicin=
g; the depositors are not reading the news and just keep their money in the=
ir checking accounts. Kind of what=E2=80=99s supposed to happen! Here=E2=80=
=99s  the Wall Street Journal yesterday:

PacWest Bancorp, which has been hit hard since the collapses of several ban=
ks, dropped by about 50%. The stock started falling in after-hours trading =
Wednesday evening, after a report that it was considering selling itself.=
=C2=A0
PacWest said in a statement after midnight Eastern Time Thursday that its c=
ore customer deposits were up since the end of the first quarter, and that =
it hadn=E2=80=99t experienced any unusual deposit flows since the collapse =
of First Republic.=C2=A0

And here=E2=80=99s   Bloomberg News this morning:

PacWest Bancorp led a rebound across US regional banking stocks after a bru=
ising week of losses, amid signals that some of the selling has been overdo=
ne.
PacWest=E2=80=99s shares soared as much as 88% in US trading Friday, their =
biggest intraday gain ever, after multiple trading pauses for volatility, w=
hile Western Alliance Bancorp rose as much as 43%.=C2=A0

 And:

Take Western Alliance, the Phoenix, Arizona-based bank whose shares tanked =
as much as 27% on Tuesday, the day after=C2=A0JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99=
s emergency rescue of First Republic Bank. While the deal failed to quell i=
nvestor concerns the upheaval would spread, depositors were a little less f=
azed: Between Monday and Tuesday, they added $600 million of cash to the ba=
nk.
=E2=80=9CThe bank has not experienced unusual deposit flows following the s=
ale of First Republic Bank and other recent industry news,=E2=80=9D Western=
 Alliance said in a=C2=A0statement, outlining that deposits had increased t=
o $48.8 billion.=C2=A0
The same was true for rival lender=C2=A0PacWest Bancorp., which said it exp=
erienced no =E2=80=9Cout-of-the-ordinary=E2=80=9D deposits flows following =
First Republic=E2=80=99s sale. Through Tuesday, deposits had increased sinc=
e the end of March, it=C2=A0said.

 The stock market has been pretty panicky about these banks, but their depo=
sitors, for the most part, have not been. How do you reconcile that tension=
? I think there are about four possibilities.
Possibility 1=C2=A0is that the stock market is correctly reflecting a risk =
of imminent=C2=A0failure at these banks, and the information-insensitive de=
positors are ignoring it. This would be somewhat weird. The way for that fa=
ilure to happen would be through=C2=A0deposit flight, and if the deposits a=
re fine and stable then it is hard to see how the banks would fail now. But=
 one can=E2=80=99t entirely rule it out; the theory here is something like =
=E2=80=9Cthe stock market knows that depositors will flee before the deposi=
tors themselves do,=E2=80=9D which kind of is=C2=A0how the stock market is =
supposed to work.
  [3]

Possibility 2 is that the stock market is overreacting, because that=E2=80=
=99s also what the stock market does. After all, these stocks got crushed y=
esterday and then soared this morning, without=C2=A0much=C2=A0in the way of=
 intervening news; both moves can=E2=80=99t really be right. Investors deci=
ded =E2=80=9Cthis is a bad week for regional banks,=E2=80=9D and so they so=
ld regional bank stocks, and then they realized that these banks were not p=
articularly close to failure, and then they bought the stocks back. Bloombe=
rg News again:
In a Friday morning note upgrading Western Alliance, Comerica and Zions to =
overweight, JPMorgan analyst Steven Alexopoulos said that the sell-off had =
fed on itself. =E2=80=9CWith sentiment this negative, in our view it won=E2=
=80=99t take much to see a significant intermediate-term favorable re-ratin=
g of regional bank stocks,=E2=80=9D he wrote.
And here=E2=80=99s  Alexandra Scaggs at FT Alphaville:

If a new challenge to regional banks has surfaced just this week, it=E2=80=
=99s a tough one to find. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe thing I can=E2=80=99t wrap my brain around is that we have zer=
o evidence =E2=80=94 and if anything we have contrary evidence =E2=80=94 th=
at there is still concerted deposit flight in the system=E2=80=9D, CreditSi=
ghts=E2=80=99 Jesse Rosenthal told Alphaville this week.

Sometimes the stock market just gets too excited, and then walks it back.
Possibility 3 is that the stock market=E2=80=99s fall yesterday=C2=A0correc=
tly reflected,=C2=A0not=C2=A0a risk of imminent failure, but long-term busi=
ness problems at these banks. The problem for PacWest, on this view, is not=
 that it might get shut down this weekend; the problem is that some of its =
deposits have left and been replaced with more expensive funding, and other=
 deposits have stayed because it has raised the interest rates it offers, a=
nd PacWest going forward will have to pay a lot for deposits and won=E2=80=
=99t earn that much on its assets and will just not be that profitable. Whi=
ch is totally fine, for depositors, and for regulators: The money will stil=
l be there. It=E2=80=99s just bad for shareholders, and=C2=A0the shareholde=
rs noticed and sold the stock. My Bloomberg Opinion colleague  Paul Davies =
writes:
  [4]


Since mid-March smaller US banks have had to compete ever harder for deposi=
t funding because of the safe-haven attractions of the biggest lenders plus=
 the higher returns already available from money market funds. The result i=
s a sharp rise in funding costs for lenders like PacWest.
PacWest has become more reliant on higher cost consumer and brokered time d=
eposits, which lifted its total deposit cost to 1.98% in the first quarter =
of 2023 from 1.37% in the previous three months. It has also borrowed more =
from costlier sources like the Federal Home Loan Banks, the Federal Reserve=
=E2=80=99s Bank Term Funding Program and capital markets. Taken together th=
ese changes helped to slash its net interest margin to 2.89% in the first q=
uarter from a fairly consistent 3.4% last year. Analysts expect it to fall =
further to about 2.5% on average for this year, according to data complied =
by Bloomberg.=C2=A0
The squeeze on lending margins hurts revenue and profitability. The last tw=
o quarters have produced its lowest pre-tax profits since the third quarter=
 of 2020. Its next two quarters are forecast to be even worse.=C2=A0

This is the most straightforward possibility: This week the stock market no=
ticed, not that the regional banks are=C2=A0failing, but that they are unpr=
ofitable, so their stocks went down. (Also they are up today, which could j=
ust be =E2=80=9Cthe stock market noticed that a little too hard yesterday,=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe stock market got a little too optimistic today,=
=E2=80=9D or some combination.)
The problem with this possibility is that it is a little=C2=A0hard to disti=
nguish it from Possibility 1. If a bank=E2=80=99s stock falls 50% in a day,=
 it=E2=80=99s sort of natural to panic, to read it as more =E2=80=9Cthe mar=
ket thinks this bank is toast=E2=80=9D than =E2=80=9Cthe market thinks that=
 the present value of the residual cash flows to shareholders will be consi=
derably lower than previously expected.=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s bad because, again, a bank run is about deposits suddenly be=
coming=C2=A0information-sensitive. One way for that to happen is that you a=
re a depositor at PacWest, you do not pay very much attention to your check=
ing account, and then you turn on the news and everyone is shouting that Pa=
cWest=E2=80=99s stock is collapsing because the market expects it to fail. =
You might start paying attention! Davies again:
Weaker profits degrade the value of its shares. But the current fear of wid=
er instability has made these problems more dangerous by creating a feedbac=
k loop: Falling share prices make depositors more skittish, funding costs r=
ise further, profitability worsens and around it goes again.=C2=A0
This brings us to Possibility 4. Possibility 4 is that stock investors were=
 pushing down the prices of regional banks in order to cause them to fail.=
=C2=A0 Here is  a Twitter thread from Bob Elliott stating the case:

Regional bank 'crisis' shifting from deposit runs driving equity declines t=
o speculators engineering equity declines to increase the risk of deposit r=
uns.
This new phase divorced from fundamentals risks creating a metastasizing cr=
isis rewarding speculative attacks. ...
Since last week there has been acute downward pressure across regional bank=
s stocks, particularly focused on $PACW and $WAL. =C2=A0
What has been driving those losses? =C2=A0Short selling & put activity. =E2=
=80=A6
The reality is that it doesn't take much flow at this point to create big m=
oves given the market caps are on the order of $1-2bln. Tiny companies rela=
tive to their macro impact right now. ...
Their funding conditions have remained *stable* through this period. =C2=A0=
Incremental information about fundamentals isn't driving the decline. =C2=
=A0Looks like speculators trying to engender a panic.

The point here is not just =E2=80=9Cpeople are shorting these bank stocks f=
or no good fundamental reason,=E2=80=9D but also that=C2=A0this can create =
fundamental problems. Elliott goes on:

In most industries if this sort of dynamic happened where there was a big h=
it to the stocks which didn't reflect a change in underlying fundamentals, =
there wouldn't be much impact on the business. =C2=A0It would keep doing it=
s thing, and eventually the stock would simply reprice.
But banks are a very different sort of business. =C2=A0They are a confidenc=
e business more than anything. =C2=A0And big stock price declines are a pro=
blem for confidence.
At some point these declines *will be enough* to start to worry uninsured d=
epositors who are paying attention.
And when that happens the fundamentals will deteriorate, which will further=
 reinforce the equity market action. Shorts will get paid for being the ver=
y folks inducing the bank run.

I am temperamentally not disposed to believe any theory like =E2=80=9Cshort=
 sellers are dishonestly manipulating this stock in order to cause the comp=
any to fail,=E2=80=9D but I have to admit that, with regional banks (unlike=
 most companies!),=C2=A0that could kinda work. Banks do rely on confidence,=
 and a plunging stock price that gets a lot of attention is bad for confide=
nce.
  [5]
 And people do seem to be taking this theory seriously.  Reuters reports:

U.S. federal and state officials are assessing whether "market manipulation=
" caused the recent volatility in banking shares, a source familiar with th=
e matter said on Thursday, as the White House vowed to monitor "short-selli=
ng pressures on healthy banks." ...
"State and federal regulators and officials are increasingly attentive to t=
he possibility of market manipulation regarding banking equities," the sour=
ce said.
White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre said the Biden administratio=
n was closely watching on the situation, but any possible action would be t=
aken by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
"The administration is going to closely monitor the market developments, in=
cluding the short-selling pressures on healthy banks," Jean-Pierre told a W=
hite House briefing.
The American Bankers Association on Thursday called on the SEC to investiga=
te significant short sales of banking shares and social media engagement th=
at it said appeared to be "disconnected from the underlying financial reali=
ties."

And at Semafor, Liz Hoffman asks, =E2=80=9CShould the U.S. ban bank short s=
elling?=E2=80=9D

In September 2008, U.S. and U.K. regulators temporarily banned investors fr=
om selling short financial stocks. =E2=80=9CUnbridled short selling is cont=
ributing to the recent, sudden price declines,=E2=80=9D then-SEC Chairman C=
hris Cox said, noting that banks (at the time, investment banks were the pr=
oblem) are uniquely vulnerable to =E2=80=9Cpanic selling because they depen=
d on the confidence of their trading counterparties in the conduct of their=
 core business.=E2=80=9D
Swap depositors for counterparties and you=E2=80=99ve pretty well got the c=
urrent problem. And investors seem to be getting ahead of customers in thei=
r rush for the exits. PacWest and Western Alliance actually added deposits =
in April, after the collapse of SVB and Signature. Fed Chair Jerome Powell =
said yesterday that the deposit outflows at regional banks had stabilized.
Depositors are no longer panicking, but investors are. It might be time to =
consider another temporary ban.

Incidentally there are stronger and weaker forms of Possibility 4. The stro=
ng form is something like =E2=80=9Cdastardly short sellers are knowingly sh=
orting stocks of regional banks with the goal of causing panic and driving =
them into failure, so they can take profits.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The weak form is=
 something like =E2=80=9Crational market participants look at the stocks of=
 regional banks and conclude that they are overvalued,=C2=A0because they ho=
nestly (correctly or incorrectly) believe that earnings will be lower or fa=
ilure more likely than the market thinks, so they short the stocks, which=
=C2=A0might cause them to fail=C2=A0and generate profits for the short sell=
ers.=E2=80=9D The=C2=A0effect=C2=A0can exist with or without the=C2=A0inten=
t.

