      Pacific West (not that one!)
   =20
 =20

The Pacific Ocean is to the west of the western part of the US. The US has =
like a zillion banks, most of them pretty local. Often they have blandly ge=
ographical names. If you are a bank in the western part of the US, sorta ne=
ar the ocean, your name might well include the words=C2=A0=E2=80=9CPacific=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwest=E2=80=9D or both. The western part of the US is =
large and has a lot of coastline, and also a lot of banks, so it should not=
 be surprising that there is both a =E2=80=9CPacific West Bancorp=E2=80=9D =
(the holding company for Pacific West=C2=A0Bank) and a =E2=80=9CPacWest Ban=
corp=E2=80=9D (the holding company for Pacific Western Bank), or that they =
are entirely different banks. PacWest Bancorp=E2=80=99s stock has had a wil=
d ride=C2=A0in recent days. Pacific West Bancorp=E2=80=99s stock has not. I=
t would like to keep it that way:

Pacific West Bancorp, a small lender based outside Portland, Oregon, is see=
king to distance itself from a California company with a similar moniker,=
=C2=A0PacWest Bancorp, whose shares have plummeted amid the recent regional=
-banking turmoil.
=E2=80=9CRecent local and national news reports have highlighted the financ=
ial difficulties of a bank with a similar name in California, leading to co=
ncerns that PWB may also be facing similar challenges,=E2=80=9D West Linn, =
Oregon-based Pacific West Bancorp said in a=C2=A0statement=C2=A0Thursday. =
=E2=80=9CHowever, PWB wants to make it clear that it is a separate entity w=
ith no affiliation to the California-based bank.=E2=80=9D
The company with a similar name, Beverly Hills-based PacWest Bancorp, has s=
ought to calm its own investors, reporting that core deposits have increase=
d since March and confirming it=E2=80=99s in talks with several potential i=
nvestors after a stock rout made it the new focal point of concern over the=
 health of US regional lenders. Still, its shares plunged as much as 61% Th=
ursday, and are down more than 85% this year.

I once=C2=A0joked on Twitter that the =E2=80=9Cbiggest risk to the US banki=
ng system is there are 4000 banks and they all have like six names.=E2=80=
=9D That was in response to a   Bloomberg News story about Republic First B=
ancorp, which put out a statement saying that it was not First Republic Ban=
k. Easy mistake to make! First Republic  was seized by the Federal Deposit =
Insurance Corp. last weekend; Republic First is fine I guess. The US is a r=
epublic, and banks tend to get ordinal numbers that restart frequently (exc=
ept poor  Fifth Third), so there are a lot of US banks with =E2=80=9CRepubl=
ic=E2=80=9D in their names, and a lot with =E2=80=9CFirst,=E2=80=9D and the=
 combination can=E2=80=99t be that rare.=C2=A0
One of my favorite banking stories of all time is when   Amalgamated Bank a=
greed to acquire Amalgamated Bank, though eventually that amalgamation was =
called off due to regulatory opposition. As far as I know both the Amalgama=
ted Banks, and any additional Amalgamated Banks, are fine, but you can see =
how this creates confusion.
I suppose the solution to the current regional banking crisis might involve=
 a lot of banking industry consolidation, and while the simplest version of=
 that is probably just for JPMorgan Chase & Co. to buy everyone, a tidier a=
nd funnier version might be for all the banks with similar names to merge w=
ith each other. How many Pac(ific) West Bancorps do we really need?

