      If the SEC allows a company to go public, does that mean that the com=
pany=E2=80=99s business is legal?
   =20
 =20

No, but, I mean, I can see  how the company would think that?

With the Securities and Exchange Commission preparing an enforcement action=
 that threatens much of its business, crypto exchange Coinbase is trying a =
novel defense. It says regulators bear some responsibility for letting the =
company go public in the first place.
Coinbase went public in April 2021 after clearing a six-month review. SEC s=
taff bored into its financial reporting and disclosures as well as the comp=
any=E2=80=99s belief that its menu of cryptocurrencies shouldn=E2=80=99t be=
 treated as securities, which the SEC regulates. Coinbase=E2=80=99s lawyers=
 argue that by clearing the review, regulators signaled that they =E2=80=9C=
did not think Coinbase=E2=80=99s core business was unlawful.=E2=80=9D
But the going-public process isn=E2=80=99t designed to judge whether risks =
to a company=E2=80=99s future should stop it from selling shares to investo=
rs, according to securities lawyers. Other companies whose business models =
were illegal at the federal or local level have been able to go public, inc=
luding cannabis firms, gaming businesses and ride-sharing companies. The SE=
C=E2=80=99s review solely examines how companies disclose those risks to in=
vestors in their regulated filings, lawyers said.

I think that in some crude practical sense Coinbase is right: If it filed t=
o go public=C2=A0today, instead of in 2020 (for a 2021 offering), the crypt=
o-hostile, Gary Gensler-led SEC probably=C2=A0would find reasons to delay i=
ts initial public=C2=A0offering indefinitely. So =E2=80=9Cthe SEC let us go=
 public in 2021=E2=80=9D does kind of mean=C2=A0something like =E2=80=9Cthe=
 SEC did not think we were totally illegal in 2021.=E2=80=9D And there is s=
ome force to the argument =E2=80=9Clook if you thought we were legal in 202=
1 after a thorough review, it seems kind of unfair for you to say we=E2=80=
=99re illegal and try to shut us down in 2023.=E2=80=9D
Of course the background fact is that between late 2020 when Coinbase filed=
 to go public, and early 2023 when the SEC has started rumbling about a   C=
oinbase enforcement action, the presidential administration and the SEC=E2=
=80=99s leadership changed, and it is now much more skeptical of crypto. Co=
inbase  went public three days before Gensler was  sworn in at the SEC; he =
was just a bit too late to stop the IPO.
But=C2=A0technically=C2=A0nothing works that way;=C2=A0technically=C2=A0the=
 SEC never gave any official approval of Coinbase=E2=80=99s business model,=
 and=C2=A0technically=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou let us get away with doing illegal =
stuff for a few years so you can=E2=80=99t stop us now=E2=80=9D is not a go=
od legal argument. But I see why they=E2=80=99re annoyed.

