<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about it is that the stock ma=
rket is supposed to be efficient and the market for bank deposits is not. T=
he point of the stock market is that a lot of well-informed hedge fund mana=
gers and hard-working analysts and Reddit-reading day traders are all compe=
ting with each other to find out information about each company and use tha=
t information to determine the fair value of its stock. The price of a stoc=
k changes each second to reflect the information and views collected by the=
 market, and if the market is working well then that price reflects the col=
lective best guess at the long-term value of the company. In practice the m=
arket sometimes tries too hard, and stock prices bounce around=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuanN0b3Iub3JnL3N0YWJsZS8xODAyNzg5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3480d5d5" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">more than is justified</a> by changes in fundamental information, b=
ut this is the goal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of a checking account is that you pu=
t your money there and=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>think about it. You=
=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>compete with a bunch of hedge fund manage=
rs to understand your bank=E2=80=99s financial statements; you=C2=A0<em>don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>stay up late reading Reddit for clues about its=C2=A0b=
usiness prospects; you maybe aren=E2=80=99t even aware of the interest rate=
 that it pays you. A checking account is not a high-risk, high-reward finan=
cial instrument that you have spent a long time doing due diligence on. It=
=E2=80=99s just money in the bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Economists say that bank deposits are supposed=
 to be =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31=
392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmJlci5vcmcvcGFwZXJzL3cyNjA3NA/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc50f4d4e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">information-insensitive</a>,=E2=80=9D and the=
re is a vast corporate-finance and regulatory apparatus to make that mostly=
 true. Most people=E2=80=99s bank accounts, for instance, are insured (up t=
o $250,000) by the=C2=A0Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., so that even if th=
eir bank=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>just cobwebs and fraud they still get their =
money back, which means that they truly=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>ne=
ed to do any diligence on their bank.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> But also banks have capital and liquidity requirements and prudential =
regulation and access to Federal Reserve lending facilities, so that even i=
f things go pretty wrong at a bank it will still have enough money to pay o=
ut its depositors, because =E2=80=9Cthe depositors don=E2=80=99t need to wo=
rry about their deposits=E2=80=9D is kind of the whole point of bank deposi=
ts. Lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers, regulators, economists =E2=80=94=
 think about these things,=C2=A0<em>so that depositors never have to</em>.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, this is not always true.=C2=A0The classic=
 story of a bank run is something like =E2=80=9Cdeposits suddenly become in=
formation-sensitive, and you don't want that.=E2=80=9D One way to tell the =
story of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.=
261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMt=
MTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwNTIzX01=
PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm=
09MjMwNTA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB548df00=
5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s collapse</a> is that its balan=
ce sheet got pretty rickety, shareholders saw that and said =E2=80=9Cwell t=
hat=E2=80=99s fine, you can have a bank with a rickety balance sheet as lon=
g as it keeps its deposits,=E2=80=9D and the stock muddled along for a whil=
e. But then=C2=A0<em>depositors=C2=A0</em>noticed that the balance sheet wa=
s rickety, they pulled their money, and the bank collapsed instantly. In fa=
ct, depositors might have noticed the problem because SVB publicly announce=
d a share sale, which put more focus on its problems. It=C2=A0<a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
ud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9ob3ctZ29sZG1hbnMtcGxhbi10by1zaG9yZS11cC1zaWxpY29uLX=
ZhbGxleS1iYW5rLWNydW1ibGVkLTk2YmI0NGJi/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a252a59" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"><em>actually found enough buyers for the stock</em></a>=C2=A0at a de=
cent price,=C2=A0but then had to pull the deal because so many deposits had=
 vanished: SVB=E2=80=99s shareholders were=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>informat=
ion-sensitive, briefly, than its depositors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the story of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0the second hal=
f of this week? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0in the US regional bank mini-crisis seems to=
 be that the stocks of some regional banks are=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>vola=
tile, while their deposits are not. The shareholders are reading the news a=
nd alternately panicking and rejoicing; the depositors are not reading the =
news and just keep their money in their checking accounts. Kind of what=E2=
=80=99s supposed to happen! Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2=
xlcy9yZWdpb25hbC1iYW5rLXNoYXJlcy1kaXZlLWFzLWludmVzdG9ycy1mcmV0LWFib3V0LWNvb=
nRhZ2lvbi03NzE3YzkxYT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
eec63b9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> the Wall Street Journal yesterday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest Bancorp, which has been hit hard since=
 the collapses of several banks, dropped by about 50%. The stock started fa=
lling in after-hours trading Wednesday evening, after a report that it was =
considering selling itself.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest said in a statement after midnight Eas=
tern Time Thursday that its core customer deposits were up since the end of=
 the first quarter, and that it hadn=E2=80=99t experienced any unusual depo=
sit flows since the collapse of First Republic.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDUvcGFjd2VzdC1sZWFkcy1yZWdpb25hbC1iYW5r=
LXN0b2NrLXJlYm91bmQtYWZ0ZXItYnJ1aXNpbmctcm91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA1MjNfTU9ORVl=
TVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMz=
A1MDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a27aa24" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  Bloomberg News this morning</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest Bancorp led a rebound across US region=
al banking stocks after a bruising week of losses, amid signals that some o=
f the selling has been overdone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest=E2=80=99s shares soared as much as 88%=
 in US trading Friday, their biggest intraday gain ever, after multiple tra=
ding pauses for volatility, while Western Alliance Bancorp rose as much as =
43%.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vYmFua2lu=
Zy1sYXcvcGFjd2VzdC13ZXN0ZXJuLWFsbGlhbmNlLWRlcG9zaXRvcnMtc2l0LXRpZ2h0LWluLXN=
0b2NrLXR1cm1vaWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae94ec05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> And</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Take Western Alliance, the Phoenix, Arizona-ba=
sed bank whose shares tanked as much as 27% on Tuesday, the day after=C2=A0=
JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99s emergency rescue of First Republic Bank.=
 While the deal failed to quell investor concerns the upheaval would spread=
, depositors were a little less fazed: Between Monday and Tuesday, they add=
ed $600 million of cash to the bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe bank has not experienced unusual =
deposit flows following the sale of First Republic Bank and other recent in=
dustry news,=E2=80=9D Western Alliance said in a=C2=A0statement, outlining =
that deposits had increased to $48.8 billion.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The same was true for rival lender=C2=A0PacWes=
t Bancorp., which said it experienced no =E2=80=9Cout-of-the-ordinary=E2=80=
=9D deposits flows following First Republic=E2=80=99s sale. Through Tuesday=
, deposits had increased since the end of March, it=C2=A0said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDUvcGFjd2VzdC1sZWFkcy1yZWdpb25hbC1iYW5rLXN0b2NrLXJlYm91bmQ=
tYWZ0ZXItYnJ1aXNpbmctcm91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDUmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC1a27aa24" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> </a>The stoc=
k market has been pretty panicky about these banks, but their depositors, f=
or the most part, have not been. How do you reconcile that tension? I think=
 there are about four possibilities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Possibility 1=C2=A0is that the stock market is=
 correctly reflecting a risk of imminent=C2=A0failure at these banks, and t=
he information-insensitive depositors are ignoring it. This would be somewh=
at weird. The way for that failure to happen would be through=C2=A0<em>depo=
sit flight</em>, and if the deposits are fine and stable then it is hard to=
 see how the banks would fail now. But one can=E2=80=99t entirely rule it o=
ut; the theory here is something like =E2=80=9Cthe stock market knows that =
depositors will flee before the depositors themselves do,=E2=80=9D which ki=
nd of <em>is=C2=A0</em>how the stock market is supposed to work.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Possibility 2 is that the stock market is over=
reacting, because that=E2=80=99s also what the stock market does. After all=
, these stocks got crushed yesterday and then soared this morning, without=
=C2=A0much=C2=A0in the way of intervening news; both moves can=E2=80=99t re=
ally be right. Investors decided =E2=80=9Cthis is a bad week for regional b=
anks,=E2=80=9D and so they sold regional bank stocks, and then they realize=
d that these banks were not particularly close to failure, and then they bo=
ught the stocks back. Bloomberg News again:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a Friday morning note upgrading=
 Western Alliance, Comerica and Zions to overweight, JPMorgan analyst Steve=
n Alexopoulos said that the sell-off had fed on itself. =E2=80=9CWith senti=
ment this negative, in our view it won=E2=80=99t take much to see a signifi=
cant intermediate-term favorable re-rating of regional bank stocks,=E2=80=
=9D he wrote.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2Nvb=
nRlbnQvOGVjNGVjNmEtMjI4Zi00YTU0LTkxYTMtYzE0OTIwMzU4Yzhk/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB165d8246" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> Alexandra Scaggs at FT Alphaville</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a new challenge to regional banks has surfa=
ced just this week, it=E2=80=99s a tough one to find. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe thing I can=E2=80=99t wrap my bra=
in around is that we have zero evidence =E2=80=94 and if anything we have c=
ontrary evidence =E2=80=94 that there is still concerted deposit flight in =
the system=E2=80=9D, CreditSights=E2=80=99 Jesse Rosenthal told Alphaville =
this week.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes the stock market just gets too excit=
ed, and then walks it back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Possibility 3 is that the stock market=E2=80=
=99s fall yesterday=C2=A0correctly reflected,=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>a risk=
 of imminent failure, but long-term business problems at these banks. The p=
roblem for PacWest, on this view, is not that it might get shut down this w=
eekend; the problem is that some of its deposits have left and been replace=
d with more expensive funding, and other deposits have stayed because it ha=
s raised the interest rates it offers, and PacWest going forward will have =
to pay a lot for deposits and won=E2=80=99t earn that much on its assets an=
d will just not be that profitable. Which is totally fine, for depositors, =
and for regulators: The money will still be there. It=E2=80=99s just bad <e=
m>for shareholders</em>, and=C2=A0the shareholders noticed and sold the sto=
ck. My Bloomberg Opinion colleague <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvYmFua2luZy1jcmlzaXMtcHJvZml0YWJpbGl0eS13YXMtb=
mV4dC1zaG9lLXRvLWRyb3AtYXQtcGFjd2VzdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDUmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB56ea566b" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Pa=
ul Davies writes</a>:<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since mid-March smaller US banks have had to c=
ompete ever harder for deposit funding because of the safe-haven attraction=
s of the biggest lenders plus the higher returns already available from mon=
ey market funds. The result is a sharp rise in funding costs for lenders li=
ke PacWest.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest has become more reliant on higher cost=
 consumer and brokered time deposits, which lifted its total deposit cost t=
o 1.98% in the first quarter of 2023 from 1.37% in the previous three month=
s. It has also borrowed more from costlier sources like the Federal Home Lo=
an Banks, the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s Bank Term Funding Program and capit=
al markets. Taken together these changes helped to slash its net interest m=
argin to 2.89% in the first quarter from a fairly consistent 3.4% last year=
. Analysts expect it to fall further to about 2.5% on average for this year=
, according to data complied by Bloomberg.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The squeeze on lending margins hurts revenue a=
nd profitability. The last two quarters have produced its lowest pre-tax pr=
ofits since the third quarter of 2020. Its next two quarters are forecast t=
o be even worse.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the most straightforward possibility: =
This week the stock market noticed, not that the regional banks are=C2=A0<e=
m>failing</em>, but that they are <em>unprofitable</em>, so their stocks we=
nt down. (Also they are up today, which could just be =E2=80=9Cthe stock ma=
rket noticed that a little too hard yesterday,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe sto=
ck market got a little too optimistic today,=E2=80=9D or some combination.)=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem with this possibility is that it i=
s a little=C2=A0hard to distinguish it from Possibility 1. If a bank=E2=80=
=99s stock falls 50% in a day, it=E2=80=99s sort of natural to panic, to re=
ad it as more =E2=80=9Cthe market thinks this bank is toast=E2=80=9D than =
=E2=80=9Cthe market thinks that the present value of the residual cash flow=
s to shareholders will be considerably lower than previously expected.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s bad because, again, a bank run =
is about deposits suddenly becoming=C2=A0information-sensitive. One way for=
 that to happen is that you are a depositor at PacWest, you do not pay very=
 much attention to your checking account, and then you turn on the news and=
 everyone is shouting that PacWest=E2=80=99s stock is collapsing because th=
e market expects it to fail. You might start paying attention! Davies again=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weaker profits degrade the value o=
f its shares. But the current fear of wider instability has made these prob=
lems more dangerous by creating a feedback loop: Falling share prices make =
depositors more skittish, funding costs rise further, profitability worsens=
 and around it goes again.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This brings us to Possibility 4. Possibility 4=
 is that stock investors were pushing down the prices of regional banks <em=
>in order to cause them to fail.</em>=C2=A0 Here is <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvb=
S9Cb2JFVW5saW1pdGVkL3N0YXR1cy8xNjU0MjUxMjc1NzAwMTA5MzE4/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB44ed38ac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> a Twitter thread from Bob Elliott</a> stating the =
case:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regional bank 'crisis' shifting from deposit r=
uns driving equity declines to speculators engineering equity declines to i=
ncrease the risk of deposit runs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This new phase divorced from fundamentals risk=
s creating a metastasizing crisis rewarding speculative attacks. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since last week there has been acute downward =
pressure across regional banks stocks, particularly focused on $PACW and $W=
AL. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What has been driving those losses? =C2=A0Shor=
t selling &amp; put activity. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reality is that it doesn't take much flow =
at this point to create big moves given the market caps are on the order of=
 $1-2bln. Tiny companies relative to their macro impact right now. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Their funding conditions have remained *stable=
* through this period. =C2=A0Incremental information about fundamentals isn=
't driving the decline. =C2=A0Looks like speculators trying to engender a p=
anic.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point here is not just =E2=80=9Cpeople are=
 shorting these bank stocks for no good fundamental reason,=E2=80=9D but al=
so that=C2=A0<em>this can create fundamental problems</em>. Elliott goes on=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In most industries if this sort of dynamic hap=
pened where there was a big hit to the stocks which didn't reflect a change=
 in underlying fundamentals, there wouldn't be much impact on the business.=
 =C2=A0It would keep doing its thing, and eventually the stock would simply=
 reprice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But banks are a very different sort of busines=
s. =C2=A0They are a confidence business more than anything. =C2=A0And big s=
tock price declines are a problem for confidence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point these declines *will be enough* =
to start to worry uninsured depositors who are paying attention.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And when that happens the fundamentals will de=
teriorate, which will further reinforce the equity market action. Shorts wi=
ll get paid for being the very folks inducing the bank run.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am temperamentally not disposed to believe a=
ny theory like =E2=80=9Cshort sellers are dishonestly manipulating this sto=
ck in order to cause the company to fail,=E2=80=9D but I have to admit that=
, with regional banks (unlike most companies!),=C2=A0<em>that could kinda w=
ork</em>. Banks do rely on confidence, and a plunging stock price that gets=
 a lot of attention is bad for confidence.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> And people do seem to be taking this theory seriously. <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
mV1dGVycy5jb20vbWFya2V0cy91cy91cy1vZmZpY2lhbHMtYXNzZXNzaW5nLXBvc3NpYmxlLW1h=
bmlwdWxhdGlvbi1iYW5raW5nLXNoYXJlcy1zb3VyY2UtMjAyMy0wNS0wNC8/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB340c4bda" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Reuters reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">U.S. federal and state officials are assessing=
 whether "market manipulation" caused the recent volatility in banking shar=
es, a source familiar with the matter said on Thursday, as the White House =
vowed to monitor "short-selling pressures on healthy banks." ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"State and federal regulators and officials ar=
e increasingly attentive to the possibility of market manipulation regardin=
g banking equities," the source said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre=
 said the Biden administration was closely watching on the situation, but a=
ny possible action would be taken by the Securities and Exchange Commission=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"The administration is going to closely monito=
r the market developments, including the short-selling pressures on healthy=
 banks," Jean-Pierre told a White House briefing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The American Bankers Association on Thursday c=
alled on the SEC to investigate significant short sales of banking shares a=
nd social media engagement that it said appeared to be "disconnected from t=
he underlying financial realities."</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And at Semafor, Liz Hoffman asks, =E2=80=9C<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31392592.261430/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuc2VtYWZvci5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZS8wNS8wNC8yMDIzL3Nob3VsZC10aGUtdXMtYmFu=
LWJhbmstc2hvcnQtc2VsbGluZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d58a73f" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Shoul=
d the U.S. ban bank short selling?</a>=E2=80=9D</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In September 2008, U.S. and U.K. regulators te=
mporarily banned investors from selling short financial stocks. =E2=80=9CUn=
bridled short selling is contributing to the recent, sudden price declines,=
=E2=80=9D then-SEC Chairman Chris Cox said, noting that banks (at the time,=
 investment banks were the problem) are uniquely vulnerable to =E2=80=9Cpan=
ic selling because they depend on the confidence of their trading counterpa=
rties in the conduct of their core business.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Swap depositors for counterparties and you=E2=
=80=99ve pretty well got the current problem. And investors seem to be gett=
ing ahead of customers in their rush for the exits. PacWest and Western All=
iance actually added deposits in April, after the collapse of SVB and Signa=
ture. Fed Chair Jerome Powell said yesterday that the deposit outflows at r=
egional banks had stabilized.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Depositors are no longer panicking, but invest=
ors are. It might be time to consider another temporary ban.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally there are stronger and weaker for=
ms of Possibility 4. The strong form is something like =E2=80=9Cdastardly s=
hort sellers are knowingly shorting stocks of regional banks with the goal =
of causing panic and driving them into failure, so they can take profits.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The weak form is something like =E2=80=9Crational market par=
ticipants look at the stocks of regional banks and conclude that they are o=
vervalued,=C2=A0because they honestly (correctly or incorrectly) believe th=
at earnings will be lower or failure more likely than the market thinks, so=
 they short the stocks, which=C2=A0<em>might cause them to fail=C2=A0</em>a=
nd generate profits for the short sellers.=E2=80=9D The=C2=A0<em>effect=C2=
=A0</em>can exist with or without the=C2=A0<em>intent</em>.</p>
